== Service history ==
[[File:Waldeck-Rousseau-h78349.jpg|thumb|''Waldeck-Rousseau'' off [[Constantinople]] in 1922]]
After entering service in early and mid-1911, respectively, ''Edgar Quinet'' and ''Waldeck-Rousseau'' were assigned to the Mediterranean Fleet.<ref>Brassey, p. 56</ref> In 1913, ''Edgar Quinet'' participated in an international naval demonstration that also included British, German, and Austro-Hungarian vessels off Albania. The demonstration was a protest of the [[Siege of Scutari (1912–13)|Siege of Scutari]] during the [[First Balkan War]]; it succeeded in forcing the Serbian army to withdraw and allowing an international force to occupy the city.<ref>Vego, pp. 151–152</ref>

Both ''Edgar Quinet'' and ''Waldeck-Rousseau'' saw service in the Mediterranean during [[World War I]]. ''Edgar Quinet'' joined the hunt for the German [[battlecruiser]] {{SMS|Goeben}} in August 1914, and both ships participated in the blockade of the [[Austro-Hungarian Navy]] in the Adriatic.<ref name=GG193>Gardiner & Gray, p. 193</ref> Later in August, ''Edgar Quinet'' was present at the [[Battle of Antivari]], which saw the sinking of the Austro-Hungarian cruiser {{SMS|Zenta}}.<ref>Corbett & Newbolt, pp. 85–86</ref> While on patrol at the mouth of the Adriatic, ''Waldeck-Rousseau'' was attacked twice by Austro-Hungarian [[U-boat]]s, though neither submarine was able to hit the cruiser. During the first action in October, several Austro-Hungarian [[destroyer]]s briefly skirmished with ''Waldeck-Rousseau'' after the U-boat attacked her.<ref>Milan, pp. 44–49, 87–89</ref> Both cruisers were involved in the seizure of [[Corfu]] in January 1916.<ref>Lauzanne, pp. 121–122</ref>

After the end of the war, both ships continued service in the eastern Mediterranean and [[Black Sea|Black]] seas. ''Waldeck-Rousseau'' joined the [[Allied intervention in the Russian Civil War]] and operated in support of the [[White movement|White Russians]] against the Red [[Bolshevik]]s; shortly after arriving, her crew mutinied over poor conditions but quickly resumed their duties.<ref>Bell & Elleman, p. 97</ref> ''Edgar Quinet'' meanwhile remained in the Mediterranean during the [[Greco-Turkish War (1919–22)|Greco-Turkish War]], and during the [[Great Fire of Smyrna]], at the climax of the conflict, she rescued 1,200 people from the city.<ref name=GG193 />

''Edgar Quinet'' was converted into a training ship in the mid-1920s, a role she filled for the remainder of the decade. On 4 January 1930, she ran aground off the Algerian coast and could not be freed.<ref>Jordan & Moulin, p. 167</ref> She sank five days later.<ref name=GG193 /> ''Waldeck-Rousseau'' had meanwhile been assigned as the [[flagship]] of the Far East fleet in 1929, where she remained until 1932, when she returned to France.<ref>Jordan & Moulin, p. 212</ref> She was decommissioned upon arrival, [[hulk (ship)|hulked]] in 1936,<ref name=G307 /> and broken up for scrap in 1941–44.<ref>Gardiner & Gray, p. 192</ref>

